                    <p class="faq-answer">To find a low expense ratio ETF, you should compare funds within the same asset class. Look for core index trackers from major providers like Vanguard, iShares, or Schwab, which frequently offer expense ratios of 0.03% or lower for broad market exposure.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">What is the cheapest ETF available to retail investors?</h3>
                    <p class="faq-answer">The 'cheapest ETF' depends on the category, but broad US market and S&P 500 trackers are generally the least expensive. Certain funds like BNY Mellon's BKLC or zero-fee mutual funds from Fidelity have pushed costs effectively to zero, though traditional leaders like VTI and SPLG remain in the 0.02%-0.03% range.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">Does a lower expense ratio guarantee better ETF performance?</h3>
                    <p class="faq-answer">While lower fees mean less drag on your returns over time, a low expense ratio does not guarantee outperformance. Other factors, such as tracking difference, the fund's specific index methodology, and general market conditions, play crucial roles in total return.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">Why do expense ratios matter for long-term ETF investing?</h3>
